Installing and loading R packages

tm for text mining operations like removing numbers, special characters, punctuations and stop words (Stop words in any language are the most commonly occurring words that have very little value for NLP and should be filtered out. Examples of stop words in English are the, is, are.)

snowballc for stemming, which is the process of reducing words to their base or root form. For example, a stemming algorithm would reduce the words fishing, fished and fisher to the stem fish.

wordcloud for generating the word cloud plot.

RColorBrewer for color palettes used in various plots

syuzhet for sentiment scores and emotion classification

ggplot2 for plotting graphs

Reading the text dataset

Virtual Corpus (VCorpus): This is a container provided by the tm package to manage and manipulate a collection of text documents. Its called virtual because it doesnt load the complete text of all documents into memory at once, which can be important when dealing with large datasets. It allows you to access and process documents selectively.

*DirSource: This is a source in tm that reads in a collection of text documents from a specified directory. Its particularly useful when you have multiple text documents stored in a folder, and you want to analyze them collectively.

# Specify the directory path
cname = file.path('trump_speech\\')
# Create a virtual corpus(VCorpus) using DirSource
docs <- VCorpus(DirSource(cname))  # 'docs' is a VCorpus that represents the collection of documents in the specified directory
summary(docs)

-These modifications help standardize certain phrases and can be useful in text mining tasks where maintaining consistency in the representation of specific terms is important. If you find that these substitutions align with your objectives, they can contribute to a more uniform and analytically meaningful representation of your text data.

The last step is text stemming. It is the process of reducing the word to its root form. The stemming process simplifies the word to its common origin. For example, the stemming process reduces the words fishing, fished and fisher to its stem fish.

Stemming is a common text preprocessing technique, but its important to note that it may not always be appropriate for all NLP tasks. Stemming algorithms reduce words to their base form, but they may also introduce errors or produce results that are not actual words. Its a trade-off between simplifying the vocabulary and potentially losing some precision in the representation of words.

If stemming aligns with the goals of your text mining project and the characteristics of your data, then this preprocessing step can contribute to a more streamlined and consistent representation of words.

Building the term document matrix

  • After cleaning the text data, the next step is to count the occurrence of each word, to identify popular or trending topics.

  • Using the function TermDocumentMatrix() from the text mining package, you can build a Document Matrix a table containing the frequency of words.

### Tesxt Mining
# Build a term-document matrix
dtm <- DocumentTermMatrix(docs)  #n this matrix, rows correspond to documents, and columns correspond to terms (words). The entries in the matrix represent the frequency of each term in each document.

From the above result

Documents: There are 11 documents in your corpus.

Terms The matrix includes 3,799 unique terms (words) found across all the documents.

Non-/sparse entries: The matrix has 8,733 non-zero entries, meaning there are 8,733 instances where a term occurs in a document. The total number of potential entries is 11 (documents) multiplied by 3,799 (unique terms) = 41,789, so the matrix is sparse, with many entries being zero (33056 zero entries).

Sparsity: The sparsity of the matrix is 79%. Sparsity is a measure of how many entries in the matrix are zero. In this case, 79% of the entries are zero, indicating that the matrix is sparse, which is common in text data.

Maximal term length: The longest term (word) in the matrix has a length of 19 characters.

Weighting The matrix is weighted using term frequency (tf). Term frequency represents how often a term occurs in a document. Other weighting schemes, such as term frequency-inverse document frequency (TF-IDF), are also commonly used in text mining.

  • removeSparseTerms() function removes terms from the Document-Term Matrix (dtm) that have a sparsity greater than 0.2 (20%). The second argument (0.2) is the sparsity threshold, meaning terms that are present in less than 20% of the documents will be removed.making the matrix denser and potentially reducing its dimensions. This can be beneficial for managing the complexity of the matrix and focusing on the more informative terms.

Word Association

  • Correlation is a statistical technique that can demonstrate whether, and how strongly, pairs of variables are related. This technique can be used effectively to analyze which words occur most often in association with the most frequently occurring words in the survey responses, which helps to see the context around these words
# Term Correlations

Generate the Word Cloud

A word cloud is one of the most popular ways to visualize and analyze qualitative data. Its an image composed of keywords found within a body of text, where the size of each word indicates its frequency in that body of text.

# Word Cloud
library(wordcloud)
set.seed(142) #fix the words position on wordcloud.
wordcloud(names(freq), freq, min.freq=25) #min.freq  words whose frequency is at or above this threshold value is plotted 

set.seed(142)
wordcloud(names(freq), freq, max.words=100) #the maximum number of words to display on the plot

set.seed(142)
wordcloud(names(freq), freq, min.freq=20, scale=c(5, .1), colors=brewer.pal(6, "Dark2")) # changes word colors going from lowest to highest frequencies

### Classification
# Preprocessing:
source = DirSource('txt_sentoken\\',recursive=T)
corpus = Corpus(source)
dtm = DocumentTermMatrix(corpus,control = list(weighting = weightTfIdf,
                                                 stopwords = T, removePunctuation = T,
                                                 stemming = T))
## Warning in TermDocumentMatrix.SimpleCorpus(x, control): custom functions are
## ignored

x.df = as.data.frame(as.matrix(dtm))
# Display the dimensions of the data frame
dim(x.df)
## [1]  2000 31236
# Add a column for the class labels (assuming 0 for the first 1000 documents and 1 for the next 1000)
x.df$class_label = c(rep(0,1000),rep(1,1000))
# Create an index to sample 300 rows for testing

# Create the training set (excluding the sampled rows) and the test set (including the sampled rows)
train = x.df[-c(index,index+1000),]
test = x.df[c(index,index+1000),]

Support Vector Machine

#Support Vector Machine:
library(e1071)
# Define lists of values for the hyperparameters gamma and cost that will be used in the hyperparameter tuning process.
gamma_list <- 2 ^ seq(-20, 20, 4)
cost_list <- 2 ^ seq(-10, 10, 4)
# Tune the SVM model to find optimal hyperparameters
model.svm = tune.svm(class_label ~., data = train[,s],kernel = "radial",gamma = gamma_list, cost=cost_list)#Use the tune.svm function to find the optimal combination of hyperparameters (gamma and cost) for the radial kernel SVM.
